# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: init-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] In computing, a **daemon** is a program that runs as a background process, rather than being under the direct control of an interactive user.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] Customary convention is to name a daemon process with the letter *d* as a suffix to indicate that it's a daemon.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] For example, syslogd is a daemon that implements system logging facility, and sshd is a daemon that serves incoming SSH connections.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] Even though the concept can apply to many computing systems, the term *daemon* is used almost exclusively in the context of Unix-based systems.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] In other contexts, different terms are used for the same concept.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] Systems often start daemons at boot time that will respond to network requests, hardware activity, or other programs by performing some task.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] Daemons such as cron may also perform defined tasks at scheduled times.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] In the context of computing, the word is generally pronounced either as /ˈdiːmən/ *DEE-mən* or /ˈdeɪmən/ *DAY-mən*.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] The term was coined by the programmers at MIT's Project MAC.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] Unix systems inherited this terminology.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] Maxwell's demon is consistent with Greek mythology's interpretation of a daemon as a supernatural being working in the background.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] In the general sense, daemon is an older form of the word "demon", from the Greek δαίμων.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] Alternative terms include *service* (used in Windows, from Windows NT onwards, and later also in Linux), *started task* (IBM z/OS), and *ghost job* (XDS UTS).
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] Sometimes the more general term *server* or *server process* is used, particularly for daemons that operate as part of client-server systems.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] A daemon that connects to a computer network is a network service.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] After the term was adopted for computer use, it was incorrectly rationalized as a backronym for **d**isk **a**nd **e**xecution **mon**itor.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] In a Unix-like system, the parent process of a daemon is often, but not always, the init process.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] A daemon is usually created either by the init process directly launching the daemon, by the daemon being run by an initialization script run by init, or by the daemon being launched by a super-server launched by init.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] The init process in Research Unix and BSD starts daemons from an initialization script.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] A daemon started as a command in an initialization script must either fork a child process and then immediately exit, or must be run as a background process using &, so that the shell running the initialization script can continue after starting the daemon.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] In the former case, the daemon process run from the shell exits, thus causing init to adopt the child process that runs as the daemon; in the latter case, when the shell running the initialization script exits, the child daemon process is adopted by init.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] The versions of init in System III and in System V can run arbitrary commands and can be configured to run them once or to restart them when they terminate.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] The former mechanism can be used to run initialization scripts; daemons started from those scripts behave the same as in Research Unix and BSD.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] The latter mechanism can be used to run daemons directly from init.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] A daemon can also be launched from a user's command line.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] However, daemons launched in that fashion typically must perform other operations, such as dissociating the process from any controlling terminal (tty).
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] Such procedures are often implemented in various convenience routines such as *daemon(3)*.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] A daemon launched by an initialization script need not do these steps, but doing so allows the daemon to be restarted by a user if it exits; init itself would not restart them.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] In MS-DOS, daemon-like functionality was implemented as a terminate-and-stay-resident program (TSR).
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] In Windows, a Windows service provides the functionality of a daemon.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] It runs as a process, usually does not interact with the user (i.e. via monitor, keyboard, or mouse) and may be launched by the operating system at boot time.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] In Windows 2000 and later versions, a Windows service is configured and controlled via various interfaces including the Control Panel, the Service Control Manager `sc` command, the `net start` and `net stop` commands, PowerShell, or a custom program.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] However, any Windows application can perform the role of a daemon, not just a service, and some Windows daemons have the option of running as a normal process.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] In classic Mac OS, optional features and services were provided by system extensions and control panels – files loaded at startup time that patched the operating system.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] Later versions of classic Mac OS augmented these with faceless background applications: regular applications that ran in the background.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] To the user, these were still described as regular system extensions.
[src:init-systems/daemon-computing] The more modern macOS, which is Unix-based, uses daemons but uses the term "services" to designate software that performs functions selected from the Services menu, rather than using that term for daemons, as Windows does.
[src:init-systems/init] In Unix-like computer operating systems, **init** (short for *initialization*) is the first user-space process started during booting of the operating system.
[src:init-systems/init] Init is a daemon process that continues running until the system is shut down.
[src:init-systems/init] It is the direct or indirect ancestor of all other processes and automatically adopts all orphaned processes.
[src:init-systems/init] Init is started by the kernel during the booting process; in most Unix-like systems, a kernel panic will occur if the kernel is unable to start it or if it dies for any reason.
[src:init-systems/init] Init is typically assigned process identifier 1.
[src:init-systems/init] In Unix systems such as System III and System V, the design of init diverged from the functionality provided by the init in Research Unix and its BSD derivatives.
[src:init-systems/init] Up until the early 2010s, most Linux distributions employed a traditional init that was somewhat compatible with System V, while some distributions such as Slackware use BSD-style startup scripts, and other distributions such as Gentoo have their own customized versions.
[src:init-systems/init] Since then, most Linux distributions have employed a more modern init system, with most employing the init provided by the systemd project.
[src:init-systems/init] Some distributions have elected to create their own System V-init compatible system, such as Gentoo Linux's OpenRC and Void Linux's runit.
[src:init-systems/init] These projects typically include features originally not in System V's init, such as multi-threading or interactive init.
[src:init-systems/init] Most modern init systems are also able to dynamically start, stop and enable services after boot with prompting by the user.
[src:init-systems/init] Research Unix init runs the initialization shell script located at `/etc/rc`, then launches getty on terminals under the control of `/etc/ttys`.
[src:init-systems/init] There are no runlevels; the `/etc/rc` file determines what programs are run by init.
[src:init-systems/init] The advantage of this system is that it is simple and easy to edit manually.
[src:init-systems/init] However, new software added to the system may require changes to existing files that risk producing an unbootable system.
[src:init-systems/init] BSD init was, prior to 4.3BSD, the same as Research UNIX's init; in 4.3BSD, it added support for running a windowing system such as X on graphical terminals under the control of `/etc/ttys`.
[src:init-systems/init] To remove the requirement to edit `/etc/rc`, BSD variants have long supported a site-specific `/etc/rc.local` file that is run in a sub-shell near the end of the boot sequence.
[src:init-systems/init] A fully modular system was introduced with NetBSD 1.5 and ported to FreeBSD 5.0, OpenBSD 4.9 and successors.
[src:init-systems/init] This system executes scripts in the `/etc/rc.d` directory.
[src:init-systems/init] Unlike System V's script ordering, which is derived from the filename of each script, this system uses explicit dependency tags placed within each script.
[src:init-systems/init] The order in which scripts are executed is determined by the *rcorder* utility based on the requirements stated in these tags.
[src:init-systems/init] When compared to its predecessors, AT&T's UNIX System III introduced a new style of system startup configuration, which survived (with modifications) into UNIX System V and is therefore called the "SysV-style init".
[src:init-systems/init] At any moment, a running System V is in one of the predetermined number of states, called *runlevels*.
[src:init-systems/init] At least one runlevel is the normal operating state of the system; typically, other runlevels represent single-user mode (used for repairing a faulty system), system shutdown, and various other states.
[src:init-systems/init] Switching from one runlevel to another causes a per-runlevel set of scripts to be run, which typically mount filesystems, start or stop daemons, start or stop the X Window System, shutdown the machine, etc.
[src:init-systems/init] The runlevels in System V describe certain states of a machine, characterized by the processes and daemons running in each of them.
[src:init-systems/init] Aside from these standard ones, Unix and Unix-like systems treat runlevels somewhat differently.
[src:init-systems/init] The common denominator, the `/etc/inittab` file, defines what each configured runlevel does in a given system.
[src:init-systems/init] On Linux distributions defaulting to runlevel 5 in the table on the right, runlevel 5 invokes a multiuser graphical environment running the X Window System, usually with a display manager like GDM or KDM.
[src:init-systems/init] However, the Solaris and illumos operating systems typically reserve runlevel 5 to shut down and automatically power off the machine.
[src:init-systems/init] On most systems, all users can check the current runlevel with either the `runlevel` or `who -r` command.
[src:init-systems/init] The root user typically changes the current runlevel by running the `telinit` or `init` commands.
[src:init-systems/init] The `/etc/inittab` file sets the default runlevel with the `:initdefault:` entry.
[src:init-systems/init] On Unix systems, changing the runlevel is achieved by starting only the missing services (as each level defines only those that are started / stopped).
[src:init-systems/init] For example, changing a system from runlevel 3 to 4 might only start the local X server.
[src:init-systems/init] Going back to runlevel 3, it would be stopped again.
[src:init-systems/init] Traditionally, one of the major drawbacks of init is that it starts tasks serially, waiting for each to finish loading before moving on to the next.
[src:init-systems/init] When startup processes end up Input/output (I/O) blocked, this can result in long delays during boot.
[src:init-systems/init] Speeding up I/O, e.g. by using SSDs, may shorten the delays but it does not address the root cause.
[src:init-systems/init] 3. dinit, a service manager and init system.
[src:init-systems/init] OpenRC, a process spawner that utilizes system-provided init, while providing process isolation, parallelized startup, and service dependency; used by Alpine Linux, Gentoo and its derivatives, and available as an option in Devuan and Artix Linux.
[src:init-systems/init] 13. systemd, a software suite, full replacement for init in Linux that includes an init daemon, with concurrent starting of services, service manager, and other features.
[src:init-systems/init] Used by Debian (replaces SysV init) and Ubuntu, among other popular Linux distributions.
[src:init-systems/init] As of February 2019, systemd has been adopted by most major Linux distributions.
[src:init-systems/init] Upstart, a full replacement of init designed to start processes asynchronously.
[src:init-systems/init] Initiated by Ubuntu and used by them until 2014.
[src:init-systems/init] It was also used in Fedora 9, Red Hat Enterprise Linux 6 and Google's ChromeOS.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] In computing, the **process identifier** (a.k.a.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] **process ID** or **PID**) is a number used by most operating system kernels—such as those of Unix, macOS and Windows—to uniquely identify an active process.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] This number may be used as a parameter in various function calls, allowing processes to be manipulated, such as adjusting the process's priority or killing it altogether.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] In Unix-like operating systems, new processes are created by the `fork()` system call.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] The PID is returned to the parent process, enabling it to refer to the child in further function calls.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] The parent may, for example, wait for the child to terminate with the `waitpid()` function, or terminate the process with `kill()`.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] There are two tasks with specially distinguished process IDs: PID 0 is used for *swapper* or *sched*, which is part of the kernel and is a process that runs on a CPU core whenever that CPU core has nothing else to do.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] Linux also calls the threads of this process *idle tasks*.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] In some APIs, PID 0 is also used as a special value that always refers to the calling thread, process, or process group.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] Process ID 1 is usually the init process primarily responsible for starting and shutting down the system.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] Originally, process ID 1 was not specifically reserved for init by any technical measures: it simply had this ID as a natural consequence of being the first process invoked by the kernel.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] More recent Unix systems typically have additional kernel components visible as 'processes', in which case PID 1 is actively reserved for the init process to maintain consistency with older systems.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] Process IDs, in the first place, are usually allocated on a sequential basis, beginning at 0 and rising to a maximum value which varies from system to system.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] Once this limit is reached, allocation restarts at 300 and again increases.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] In macOS and HP-UX, allocation restarts at 100.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] However, for this and subsequent passes any PIDs still assigned to processes are skipped.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] Some consider this to be a potential security vulnerability in that it allows information about the system to be extracted, or messages to be covertly passed between processes.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] As such, implementations that are particularly concerned about security may choose a different method of PID assignment.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] On some systems, like MPE/iX, the lowest available PID is used, sometimes in an effort to minimize the number of process information kernel pages in memory.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] The current process ID is provided by a `getpid()` system call, or as a variable `$$` in shell.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] The process ID of a parent process is obtainable by a `getppid()` system call.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] On Linux, the maximum process ID is given by the pseudo-file `/proc/sys/kernel/pid_max`.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] Some processes (including many daemons, for example, the MySQL daemon), write their process ID to a documented file location, to allow other processes to look it up.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] On Microsoft Windows operating systems, one can get a current process's ID using the `GetCurrentProcessId()` function of the Windows API, and ID of other processes using `GetProcessId()`.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] Internally, process ID is called a *client ID*, and is allocated from the same namespace as thread IDs, so these two never overlap.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] The System Idle Process is given process ID 0.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] On older Windows systems, the System Process is given the process ID 8 on Windows 2000 and 4 on Windows XP and Windows Server 2003.
[src:init-systems/process-identifier] On the Windows NT family of operating systems, process and thread identifiers are all multiples of 4, but it is not part of the specification.
[src:init-systems/runit] When running as an init daemon, Runit is the direct or indirect ancestor of all other processes.
[src:init-systems/runit] It is the first process started during booting, and continues running until the system is shut down.
[src:init-systems/runit] It is often used with other init systems as a separate service manager.
[src:init-systems/runit] In the service manager role, it can be used by unprivileged users to orchestrate personal services, as well as by root to manage services not otherwise managed by the init system currently in use.
[src:init-systems/runit] Runit focuses on being a small, modular, and portable codebase.
[src:init-systems/runit] In the init role, Runit is split into three stages: one time initialization, process supervision, and halting or rebooting.
[src:init-systems/runit] While the first and third stages must be adapted to the specific operating system they are running on, the second stage is portable across all POSIX compliant operating systems.
[src:init-systems/runit] The 3 stages can be configured through 3 executable files (they are usually shell scripts) named, respectively, 1, 2, and 3.
[src:init-systems/runit] In case a daemon is added or removed, it kills the watchdog or starts a new one.
[src:init-systems/runit] Executable files with specific names are used to describe the various phases of the daemon's life (run, check, finish, ...), it can intercept signals sent and run by specific scripts if they exist, and named pipes are created to expose interfaces to control the daemon.
[src:init-systems/runit] Runit can be used either as a drop-in replacement for sysvinit, or as a service supervisor (with sysvinit as the parent PID 1 process which runs processes specified by the inittab file, or some other init system).
[src:init-systems/runit] The RubyWorks stack of software able to run Ruby on Rails incorporated Runit into its suite.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In Linux distributions, systemd is used as a replacement for Sysvinit and other init systems.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Since 2015, nearly all Linux distributions have adopted systemd.
[src:init-systems/systemd] It has been praised by developers and users of distributions that adopted it for providing a stable, fast out-of-the-box solution for issues that had existed in the Linux space for years.
[src:init-systems/systemd] At the time of its adoption, it was the only parallel boot and init system offering centralized management of processes, daemons, services, and mount points..
[src:init-systems/systemd] Critics of systemd contend it suffers from feature creep and has damaged interoperability across Unix-like operating systems (as it does not run on non-Linux Unix derivatives like BSD or Solaris).
[src:init-systems/systemd] In addition, they contend systemd's large feature set creates a larger attack surface.
[src:init-systems/systemd] This has led to the development of several minor Linux distributions replacing systemd with other init systems like SysVinit or OpenRC.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Lennart Poettering and Kay Sievers, the software engineers then working for Red Hat who initially developed systemd, started a project to replace Linux's conventional System V init in 2010.
[src:init-systems/systemd] An April 2010 blog post from Poettering, titled "Rethinking PID 1", introduced an experimental version of what would later become systemd.
[src:init-systems/systemd] They sought to surpass the efficiency of the init daemon in several ways.
[src:init-systems/systemd] They wanted to improve the software framework for expressing dependencies, to allow more processes to run concurrently or in parallel during system booting, and to reduce the computational overhead of the shell.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In May 2011, Fedora Linux became the first major Linux distribution to enable systemd by default, replacing Upstart.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The reasoning at the time was that systemd provided extensive parallelization during startup, better management of processes and overall a saner, dependency-based approach to control of the system.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In October 2012, Arch Linux made systemd the default, switching from SysVinit.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Developers had debated since August 2012 and concluded it was faster and had more features than SysVinit and that maintaining SysVinit was not worth the effort.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Some thought the criticism of systemd was not based on actual shortcomings of the software but rather personal dislike of Poettering and a general opposition to change.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Several complaints about systemd—including its use of D-bus, C instead of bash, and an optional on-disk journal format—were instead described as advantages by the Arch maintainers.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Between 2013 and 2014, the Debian Technical Committee engaged in a widely publicized debate on the mailing list about which init system to use as the default in Debian 8 before settling on systemd.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Mark Shuttleworth announced soon afterwards that the Debian-based Ubuntu would use systemd to replace its old Upstart init system.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In August 2015, systemd started providing a login shell, callable via **machinectl shell**.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In September 2016, a security bug was discovered that allowed any unprivileged user to perform a denial-of-service attack against systemd.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Rich Felker, developer of musl, stated that this bug reveals a major "system development design flaw".
[src:init-systems/systemd] In 2017 another security bug was discovered in systemd-resolved, CVE-2017-9445, which "allows disruption of service" by a "malicious DNS server".
[src:init-systems/systemd] Later in 2017, the Pwnie Awards gave author Lennart Poettering a "lamest vendor response" award due to his handling of the vulnerabilities.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Poettering describes systemd development as "never finished, never complete, but tracking progress of technology".
[src:init-systems/systemd] systemd includes features like on-demand starting of daemons, snapshot support, process tracking and Inhibitor Locks.
[src:init-systems/systemd] It is not just the name of the init daemon but also refers to the entire software bundle around it, which, in addition to the systemd init daemon, includes the daemons journald, logind and networkd, and many other low-level components.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In January 2013, Poettering described systemd not as one program, but rather a large software suite that includes 69 individual binaries.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Like the init daemon, systemd is a daemon that manages other daemons, which, including systemd itself, are background processes. systemd is the first daemon to start during booting and the last daemon to terminate during shutdown.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The systemd daemon serves as the root of the user space's process tree; the first process (PID 1) has a special role on Unix systems, as it replaces the parent of a process when the original parent terminates.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Therefore, the first process is particularly well suited for the purpose of monitoring daemons.
[src:init-systems/systemd] systemd executes elements of its startup sequence in parallel, which is theoretically faster than the traditional startup sequence approach.
[src:init-systems/systemd] For inter-process communication (IPC), systemd makes Unix domain sockets and D-Bus available to the running daemons.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The state of systemd itself can also be preserved in a snapshot for future recall.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Since version 205, systemd also offers ControlGroupInterface, which is an API to the Linux kernel cgroups.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The Linux kernel cgroups are adapted to support kernfs, and are being modified to support a unified hierarchy.
[src:init-systems/systemd] is the standard library for utilizing udev, which allows third-party applications to query udev resources.
[src:init-systems/systemd] is a daemon that manages user logins and seats in various ways.
[src:init-systems/systemd] It was integrated in systemd version 30.
[src:init-systems/systemd] is a daemon that provides portable human-user accounts that are independent of current system configuration.
[src:init-systems/systemd] may be used to review the state of the network links as seen by systemd-networkd.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Configuration of new interfaces has to be added under the /lib/systemd/network/ as a new file ending with .network extension.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Kay Sievers merged it into systemd with rev 220.
[src:init-systems/systemd] may be used to run a command or OS in a namespace container.
[src:init-systems/systemd] daemon for synchronizing the system clock across the network.
[src:init-systems/systemd] is a utility that takes care of creation and clean-up of temporary files and directories.
[src:init-systems/systemd] It is normally run once at startup and then in specified intervals.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In order to match the version number of udev, systemd maintainers bumped the version number directly from 44 to 183.
[src:init-systems/systemd] On 29 May 2014, support for firmware loading through udev was dropped from systemd, as it was decided that the kernel should be responsible for loading firmware.
[src:init-systems/systemd] systemd is configured exclusively via plain-text files although GUI tools such as systemd-manager are also available.
[src:init-systems/systemd] systemd records initialization instructions for each daemon in a configuration file (referred to as a "unit file") that uses a declarative language, replacing the traditionally used per-daemon startup shell scripts.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The syntax of the language is inspired by .ini files.
[src:init-systems/systemd] While many distributions boot systemd by default, some allow other init systems to be used; in this case switching the init system is possible by installing the appropriate packages.
[src:init-systems/systemd] A fork of Debian called Devuan was developed to avoid systemd and has reached version 5.0 for stable usage.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In December 2019, the Debian project voted in favour of retaining systemd as the default init system for the distribution, but with support for "exploring alternatives".
[src:init-systems/systemd] In the interest of enhancing the interoperability between systemd and the GNOME desktop environment, systemd coauthor Lennart Poettering asked the GNOME Project to consider making systemd an external dependency of GNOME 3.2.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In November 2012, the GNOME Project concluded that basic GNOME functionality should not rely on systemd.
[src:init-systems/systemd] However, GNOME 3.8 introduced a compile-time choice between the logind and ConsoleKit API, the former being provided at the time only by systemd.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Ubuntu provided a separate logind binary, but systemd became a *de facto* dependency of GNOME for most Linux distributions, in particular since ConsoleKit is no longer actively maintained and upstream recommends the use of systemd-logind instead.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The developers of Gentoo Linux also attempted to adapt these changes in OpenRC, but the implementation contained too many bugs, causing the distribution to mark systemd as a dependency of GNOME.
[src:init-systems/systemd] As of Mutter version 3.13.2, logind is a dependency for Wayland sessions.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The design of systemd has ignited controversy within the free-software community.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Critics regard systemd as overly complex and suffering from continued feature creep, arguing that its architecture violates the Unix philosophy.
[src:init-systems/systemd] There is also concern that it forms a system of interlocked dependencies, thereby giving distribution maintainers little choice but to adopt systemd as more user-space software comes to depend on its components.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In a 2012 interview, Slackware's lead Patrick Volkerding expressed reservations about the systemd architecture, stating his belief that its design was contrary to the Unix philosophy of interconnected utilities with narrowly defined functionalities.
[src:init-systems/systemd] As of August 2018, Slackware does not support or use systemd, but Volkerding has not ruled out the possibility of switching to it.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In January 2013, Lennart Poettering attempted to address concerns about systemd in a blog post called *The Biggest Myths*.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Raymond commented that systemd's design goals were prone to mission creep and software bloat.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In April 2014, Linus Torvalds expressed reservations about the attitude of Kay Sievers, a key systemd developer, toward users and bug reports in regard to modifications to the Linux kernel submitted by Sievers.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In late April 2014, a campaign to boycott systemd was launched, with a website listing various reasons against its adoption.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In an August 2014 article published in *InfoWorld*, Paul Venezia wrote about the systemd controversy and attributed the controversy to violation of the Unix philosophy, and to "enormous egos who firmly believe they can do no wrong".
[src:init-systems/systemd] The article also characterizes the architecture of systemd as similar to that of svchost.exe, a critical system component in Microsoft Windows with a broad functional scope.
[src:init-systems/systemd] He cited similarities with the attitude he found in the GNOME project toward non-standard configurations.
[src:init-systems/systemd] On social media, Ts'o also later compared the attitudes of Sievers and his co-developer, Lennart Poettering, to that of GNOME's developers.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Forks of systemd are closely tied to critiques of it outlined in the above section.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Forks generally try to improve on at least one of portability (to other libcs and Unix-like systems), modularity, or size.
[src:init-systems/systemd] A few forks have collaborated under the FreeInit banner.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In 2012, the Gentoo Linux project created a fork of udev in order to avoid dependency on the systemd architecture.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The resulting fork is called *eudev* and it makes udev functionality available without systemd.
[src:init-systems/systemd] A stated goal of the project is to keep eudev independent of any Linux distribution or init system.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In 2021, Gentoo announced that support of eudev would cease at the beginning of 2022.
[src:init-systems/systemd] An independent group of maintainers have since taken up eudev.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Elogind is the systemd project's "logind", extracted to be a standalone daemon.
[src:init-systems/systemd] It integrates with PAM to know the set of users that are logged into a system and whether they are logged in graphically, on the console, or remotely.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Elogind exposes this information via the standard org.freedesktop.login1 D-Bus interface, as well as through the file system using systemd's standard /run/systemd layout.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Elogind also provides "libelogind", which is a subset of the facilities offered by "libsystemd".
[src:init-systems/systemd] There is a "libelogind.pc" pkg-config file as well.
[src:init-systems/systemd] ConsoleKit was forked in October 2014 by Xfce developers wanting its features to still be maintained and available on operating systems other than Linux.
[src:init-systems/systemd] While not ruling out the possibility of reviving the original repository in the long term, the main developer considers ConsoleKit2 a temporary necessity until systembsd matures.
[src:init-systems/systemd] LoginKit was an attempt to implement a logind (systemd-logind) shim, which would allow packages that depend on systemd-logind to work without dependency on a specific init system.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The project has been defunct since February 2015.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In 2014, a Google Summer of Code project named "systembsd" was started in order to provide alternative implementations of these APIs for OpenBSD.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The original project developer began it in order to ease his transition from Linux to OpenBSD.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Project development finished in July 2016.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The systembsd project did not provide an init replacement, but aimed to provide OpenBSD with compatible daemons for hostnamed, timedated, localed, and logind.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The project did not create new systemd-like functionality, and was only meant to act as a wrapper over the native OpenBSD system.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Notsystemd intends to implement all systemd's features working on any init system.
[src:init-systems/systemd] It was forked by the Parabola GNU/Linux-libre developers to build packages with their development tools without the necessity of having systemd installed to run systemd-nspawn.
[src:init-systems/systemd] In 2014, *uselessd* was created as a lightweight fork of systemd.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The project sought to remove features and programs deemed unnecessary for an init system, as well as address other perceived faults.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Project development halted in January 2015.
[src:init-systems/systemd] uselessd supported the musl and μClibc libraries, so it may have been used on embedded systems, whereas systemd only supported glibc.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The uselessd project had planned further improvements on cross-platform compatibility, as well as architectural overhauls and refactoring for the Linux build in the future.
[src:init-systems/systemd] InitWare is a modular refactor of systemd, porting the system to BSD platforms without glibc or Linux-specific system calls.
[src:init-systems/systemd] It is known to work on DragonFly BSD, FreeBSD, NetBSD, and GNU/Linux.
[src:init-systems/systemd] Components considered unnecessary are dropped.
[src:init-systems/systemd] All Systems Go! is the annual systemd conference, which is held in Berlin.
[src:init-systems/systemd] The main topic is systemd but other Linux areas are covered as well, like TPM, DBus, desktop environment, containers, eBPF etc.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] As of 2026, the AT&T-derived Unix market is divided between three System V variants: IBM's AIX, Oracle's Solaris, and the free-software illumos forked from OpenSolaris.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] System V was the successor to 1982's UNIX System III.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] While AT&T developed and sold hardware that ran System V, most customers ran a version from a reseller, based on AT&T's reference implementation.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] A standards document called the System V Interface Definition outlined the default features and behavior of implementations.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] In the 1980s and early-1990s, UNIX System V and the Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD) were the two major versions of UNIX.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Historically, BSD was also commonly called "BSD Unix" or "Berkeley Unix".
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] While HP, IBM and others chose System V as the basis for their Unix offerings, other vendors such as Sun Microsystems and DEC extended BSD.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Throughout its development, though, System V was infused with features from BSD, while BSD variants such as DEC's Ultrix received System V features.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] AT&T and Sun Microsystems worked together to merge System V with BSD-based SunOS to produce Solaris, one of the primary System V descendants still in use today.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Since the early 1990s, due to standardization efforts such as POSIX and the success of Linux, the division between System V and BSD has become less important.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] System V, known inside Bell Labs as Unix 5.0, succeeded AT&T's previous commercial Unix called System III in January, 1983.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Unix 4.0 was never released externally, which would have been designated as System IV.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] This first release of System V (called System V.0, System V Release 1, or SVR1) was developed by AT&T's UNIX Support Group (USG) and based on the Bell Labs internal USG UNIX 5.0.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] System V also included features such as the vi editor and curses from 4.1 BSD, developed at the University of California, Berkeley; it also improved performance by adding buffer and inode caches.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] It also added support for inter-process communication using messages, semaphores, and shared memory, developed earlier for the Bell-internal CB UNIX.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] SVR1 ran on DEC PDP-11 and VAX minicomputers.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] AT&T's UNIX Support Group (USG) transformed into the UNIX System Development Laboratory (USDL), which released System V Release 2 in 1984.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] SVR2 added shell functions and the SVID.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] SVR2.4 added demand paging, copy-on-write, shared memory, and record and file locking.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] The concept of the "porting base" was formalized, and the DEC VAX-11/780 was chosen for this release.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] The "porting base" is the so-called original version of a release, from which all porting efforts for other machines emanate.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Educational source licenses for SVR2 were offered by AT&T for US$800 for the first CPU, and $400 for each additional CPU.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] A commercial source license was offered for $43,000, with three months of support, and a $16,000 price per additional CPU.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Apple Computer's A/UX operating system was initially based on this release.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Microsoft Xenix 5.0 also used SVR2 as its basis.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] The first release of HP-UX was also an SVR2 derivative.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Bach's book, *The Design of the UNIX Operating System*, is the definitive description of the SVR2 kernel, with some new features from Release 3 and BSD.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] AT&T's UNIX System Development Laboratory (USDL) was succeeded by AT&T Information Systems (ATTIS), which distributed UNIX System V, Release 3, in 1987.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] SVR3 included STREAMS, Remote File Sharing (RFS), the File System Switch (FSS) virtual file system mechanism, a restricted form of shared libraries, and the Transport Layer Interface (TLI) network API.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] The final version was Release 3.2 in 1988, which added binary compatibility to Xenix on Intel platforms (see Intel Binary Compatibility Standard).
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] User interface improvements included the "layers" windowing system for the DMD 5620 graphics terminal, and the SVR3.2 curses libraries that offered eight or more color pairs and other at this time important features (forms, panels, menus, etc.).
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] SCO UNIX was based upon SVR3.2, as was ISC 386/ix.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Among the more obscure distributions of SVR3.2 for the 386 were ESIX 3.2 by Everex and "System V, Release 3.2" sold by Intel themselves; these two shipped "plain vanilla" AT&T's codebase.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] IBM's AIX operating system is an SVR3 derivative.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] System V Release 4.0 was announced on October 18, 1988 and was incorporated into a variety of commercial Unix products from early 1989 onwards.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Many companies licensed SVR4 and bundled it with computer systems such as workstations and network servers.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Software porting houses also sold enhanced and supported Intel x86 versions.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] SVR4 software vendors included Dell (Dell UNIX), Everex (ESIX), Micro Station Technology (SVR4), Microport (SVR4), and UHC (SVR4).
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] The primary platforms for SVR4 were Intel x86 and SPARC; the SPARC version, called Solaris 2 (or, internally, SunOS 5.x), was developed by Sun.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] The relationship between Sun and AT&T was terminated after the release of SVR4, meaning that later versions of Solaris did not inherit features of later SVR4.x releases.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Sun would in 2005 release most of the source code for Solaris 10 (SunOS 5.10) as the open-source OpenSolaris project, creating, with its forks, the only open-source (albeit heavily modified) System V implementation available.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] After Oracle took over Sun, Solaris was forked into proprietary release, but illumos as the continuation project is being developed in open-source.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] A consortium of Intel-based resellers including Unisys, ICL, NCR Corporation, and Olivetti developed SVR4.0MP with multiprocessing capability (allowing system calls to be processed from any processor, but interrupt servicing only from a "master" processor).
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Release 4.1 ES (Enhanced Security) added security features required for Orange Book B2 compliance and Access Control Lists and support for dynamic loading of kernel modules.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] In 1992, AT&T USL engaged in a joint venture with Novell, called Univel.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] That year saw the release System V.4.2 as Univel UnixWare, featuring the Veritas File System.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Other vendors included UHC and Consensys.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Release **4.2MP**, completed late 1993, added support for multiprocessing and it was released as UnixWare 2 in 1995.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Raymond warned prospective buyers about SVR4.2 versions, as they often did not include on-line man pages.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] In his 1994 buyers guide, he attributes this change in policy to Unix System Laboratories.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] The Santa Cruz Operation (SCO), owners of Xenix, eventually acquired the UnixWare trademark and the distribution rights to the System V Release 4.2 codebase from Novell, while other vendors (Sun, IBM, HP) continued to use and extend System V Release 4.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Novell transferred ownership of the Unix trademark to The Open Group.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] System V Release 5 was developed in 1997 by the Santa Cruz Operation (SCO) as a merger of SCO OpenServer (an SVR3-derivative) and UnixWare, with a focus on large-scale servers.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] SCO's successor, The SCO Group, also based SCO OpenServer 6 on SVR5, but the codebase is not used by any other major developer or reseller.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] System V Release 6 was announced by SCO to be released by the end of 2004, but was apparently cancelled.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] It was supposed to support 64-bit systems.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] SCO also introduced Smallfoot in 2004, a low-resource "embeddable" variant of UnixWare for dedicated commercial and industrial applications, in an attempt that was perceived as a response to the growing popularity of Linux.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] The industry has since coalesced around The Open Group's Single UNIX Specification version 3 (UNIX 03).
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] In the 1980s and 1990s, a variety of SVR4 versions of Unix were available commercially for the x86 PC platform.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] However, the market for commercial Unix on PCs declined after Linux and BSD became widely available.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] An *InfoWorld* article from 2001 characterized SCO UnixWare as having a "bleak outlook" due to being "trounced" in the market by Linux and Solaris, and IDC predicted that SCO would "continue to see a shrinking share of the market".
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Project Monterey was started in 1998 to combine major features of existing commercial Unix platforms, as a joint project of Compaq, IBM, Intel, SCO, and Sequent Computer Systems.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] The target platform was meant to be Intel's new IA-64 architecture and Itanium line of processors.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] However, the project was abruptly canceled in 2001 after little progress.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] By 2001, several major Unix variants such as SCO UnixWare, Compaq Tru64 UNIX, and SGI IRIX were all in decline.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] The three major Unix versions doing well in the market were IBM AIX, Hewlett-Packard's HP-UX, and Sun's Solaris.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] In 2006, when SGI declared bankruptcy, analysts questioned whether Linux would replace proprietary Unix altogether.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] In a November 2015 survey of the top 500 supercomputers, Unix was used by only 1.2% (all running IBM AIX), while Linux was used by 98.8%; the same survey in November 2017 reports 100% of them using Linux.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] System V derivatives continued to be deployed on some proprietary server platforms.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] The principal variants of System V that remain in commercial use are AIX (IBM), Solaris (Oracle), and HP-UX (HP).
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] According to a study done by IDC, in 2012 the worldwide Unix market was divided between IBM (56%), Oracle (19.2%), and HP (18.6%).
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] No other commercial Unix vendor had more than 2% of the market.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Industry analysts generally characterize proprietary Unix as having entered a period of slow but permanent decline.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] OpenSolaris and its derivatives are the only SVR4 descendants that are open-source software.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Core system software continues to be developed as illumos, which is used in illumos distributions such as SmartOS, OpenIndiana and others.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] The System V interprocess communication mechanisms are available in Unix-like operating systems not derived from System V; in particular, in Linux (a reimplementation of Unix) as well as the BSD derivative FreeBSD.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] POSIX 2008 specifies a replacement for these interfaces.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] FreeBSD maintains a binary compatibility layer for the COFF format, which allows FreeBSD to execute binaries compiled for some SVR3.2 derivatives such as SCO UNIX and Interactive UNIX.
[src:init-systems/unix-system-v] Modern System V, Linux, and BSD platforms use the ELF file format for natively compiled binaries.
